{{About|physical systems|the property of an infinite word|Critical exponent of a word}}
'''Critical exponents''' describe the behavior of physical quantities near continuous [[phase transitions]]. It is believed, though not proven, that they are universal, i.e. they do not depend on the details of the physical system, but only on
* the dimension of the system
* the range of the interaction
* the [[Spin (physics)|spin]] dimension

These properties of critical exponents are supported by experimental data. Analytical results can be theoretically achieved in [[mean field theory]] for higher-dimensional systems (4 or more dimensions). The theoretical treatment of lower-dimensional systems (1 or 2 dimensions) is more difficult and requires the [[renormalization group]] approach.
Phase transitions and critical exponents appear also in percolation systems.
However, here the critical dimension above which mean field exponents are valid is 6 and higher dimensions.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-642-84868-1_2|title=Fractals and Disordered Systems|last=Bunde|first=Armin|last2=Havlin|first2=Shlomo|date=1996|publisher=Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg|year=|isbn=9783642848704|location=|pages=59–114|language=en|chapter=Percolation I|doi=10.1007/978-3-642-84868-1_2}}</ref>
Mean field critical exponents are also valid for random graphs, such as Erdős–Rényi graphs, which can be regarded as infinite dimensional systems.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://doi.org/10.1017/CBO9780511780356.001|title=Complex Networks: Structure, Robustness and Function|last=Cohen|first=Reuven|last2=Havlin|first2=Shlomo|date=2010|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=|isbn=9780521841566|location=|pages=1–6|language=en|chapter=Introduction|doi=10.1017/cbo9780511780356.001}}</ref>

==Definition==
[[Phase transitions]] occur at a certain temperature, called the [[critical temperature]] {{math|''T''<sub>c</sub>}}. We want to describe the behavior of a physical quantity {{math|''f''}} in terms of a [[power law]] around the critical temperature; we introduce the [[reduced temperature]]

:<math>\tau := \frac{T-T_\mathrm{c}}{T_\mathrm{c}}</math>

which is zero at the [[phase transition]], and define the critical exponent <math>k</math>:

:<math>k \, \stackrel{\text{def}}{=} \, \lim_{\tau \to 0}\frac{\log |f(\tau)| }{\log |\tau|}</math>

This results in the power law we were looking for:
:<math> f(\tau) \propto \tau^k \,, \quad \tau\approx 0 </math>

It is important to remember that this represents the asymptotic behavior of the function {{math|''f''(''τ'')}} as {{math|''τ'' → 0}}.

More generally one might expect
:<math>f(\tau)=A \tau^k \left(1+b\tau ^{k_1} + \cdots\right) </math>

==The most important critical exponents==
Below {{math|''T''<sub>c</sub>}} the system has two different phases characterized by an [[order parameter]] {{math|''Ψ''}}, which vanishes at and above {{math|''T''<sub>c</sub>}}.

Let us consider the [[disordered phase]] ({{math|''τ'' > 0}}), [[ordered phase]] ({{math|''τ'' < 0}}) and [[critical temperature]] ({{math|''τ'' {{=}} 0}}) phases separately. Following the standard convention, the critical exponents related to the ordered phase are primed. It is also another standard convention to use superscript/subscript + (−) for the disordered (ordered) state. We have [[spontaneous symmetry breaking]] in the ordered phase. So, we will arbitrarily take any solution in the phase.
