{{Infobox company | name = Hobart | logo = Hobart logo.svg | logo_size = 150px | type = Subsidiary of [[Illinois Tool Works]] | industry = [[Foodservice]] | foundation = {{start date and age|1897}} | hq_location_city = [[Troy, Ohio]] | hq_location_country = [[United States]] | homepage = [http://www.hobartcorp.com Hobart Corporation] }}
The '''Hobart Corporation''' is an American manufacturer of commercial equipment used in the [[foodservice]] and [[grocery]] industry. The company manufactures [[Outline of food preparation#Food preparation techniques|food preparation]] [[Home appliance|machines]] for cutting, [[Meat slicer|slicing]] and [[mixer (cooking)|mixing]], cooking equipment, [[refrigeration]] units, [[Dishwasher|warewashing]] and [[garbage disposal|waste disposal systems]], and [[Weighing scale|weighing]], wrapping, and labeling systems and products. Hobart is an international company with manufacturing plants in the US, [[Brazil]], Canada, China, [[France]], [[Germany]], [[Italy]], and the UK.<ref>{{Cite web|title=About Us|url=http://www.hobartcorp.com/about-us/|publisher=Hobart Corporation|accessdate=7 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111025050402/https://www.hobartcorp.com/about-us/ |archive-date=2011-10-25}}</ref>
== History == Hobart was founded in 1897 as the '''Hobart Electric Manufacturing Company''' in [[Troy, Ohio]], by Clarence Charles Hobart (1855-1932).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vintagemachinery.org/mfgindex/detail.aspx?id=1966 |title=Hobart Manufacturing Co. - History |date=24 December 2013 |website=Vintage Machinery}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSln=Hobart&GSiman=1&GScnty=2094&GRid=37336274& |title=Clarence Charles Hobart |website=Find a Grave}}</ref> To increase motor sales, the company attached motors to [[Coffee preparation#Grinding|coffee mill]]s and [[meat grinder]]s, creating a powered food production machine.
The company reorganized in 1913 as '''The Hobart Manufacturing Company''' and became Hobart Corporation in 1974. The former [[Kitchen Aid]] division was formed in 1919. In 1934 Hobart bought the Dayton Scale Company (an IBM division) from IBM. [[Dart & Kraft#Dart merger|Dart & Kraft]] acquired Hobart in 1981.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/02/18/business/dart-kraft-and-hobart-in-460-million-merger.html |title=DART & KRAFT AND HOBART IN $460 MILLION MERGER |date=18 Feb 1981 |first=Robert J. |last=Cole |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> Kitchen Aid was sold to [[Whirlpool Corp.]] in 1986<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/01/30/business/whirlpool-cleared-to-buy-kitchenaid.html |work=The New York Times |date=30 January 1986 |access-date=28 November 2018 |title=Whirlpool Cleared To Buy Kitchenaid}}</ref> after getting an offer, for $150 million in January 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/07/02/business/whirlpool-amends-kitchenaid-plan.html |title=Whirlpool Amends Kitchenaid Plan |date=2 July 1985 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2018-11-28}}</ref> Dart & Kraft split in 1986, with Hobart becoming part of Premark.<ref>{{cite website |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1986/09/09/business/company-news-dart-kraft-calls-spinoff-premark.html |title=Dart & Kraft Calls Spinoff 'Premark'|work=The New York Times |date=9 September 1986}}</ref> Premark was acquired by [[Illinois Tool Works]] in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-09-10/business/9909100202_1_itw-premark-international-illinois-tool-works |title=ITW Makes Big Leap With Premark |work=Chicago Tribune |date=10 September 1999 |first=Sallie L. |last=Gaines}}</ref> In 2001, Hobart became a part of [[Illinois Tool Works]] Food Equipment Group.
