{{Use Indian English|date=June 2015}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}} {{Infobox power station |name = Kakrapar Atomic Power Station |image = |image_caption = |location_map = India |country = India |coordinates = {{coord|21|14|19|N|73|21|00|E|region:IN_type:landmark_source:dewiki|display=inline,title}} |operator = [[Nuclear Power Corporation of India]] |status = Out of service for {{age in years and months|2016|3|11}}<ref name=news18>{{cite news|url= http://www.news18.com/news/tech/kakrapar-nuclear-reactors-to-get-new-coolant-channels-1343571.html|title= Kakrapar Nuclear Reactors to Get New Coolant Channels |website= [[news18.com]] |date= 2017-02-01 |accessdate= 2017-02-16}}</ref> |construction_began = 1984 |commissioned = 6 May 1993 |decommissioned = |np_reactor_type = PHWR |ps_units_operational= 2 × 220&nbsp;MW |ps_units_decommissioned= |ps_units_uc = 2 × 700 MW |ps_electrical_capacity= <!-- sum of gross operational reactor power-->440 |ps_annual_generation= 3.72 TWh |ps_electrical_cap_fac= 96.5% |website = }} '''Kakrapar Atomic Power Station''' is a [[nuclear power]] station in [[India]], which lies in the proximity of the city of [[Vyara]] in the state of [[Gujarat]]. It consists of two 220&nbsp;MW [[pressurised water reactor]] with [[heavy water]] as moderator (PHWR). KAPS-1 went critical on 3&nbsp;September 1992 and began commercial electricity production a few months later on 6&nbsp;May 1993. KAPS-2 went critical on 8&nbsp;January 1995 and began commercial production on 1 September 1995. In January 2003, [[CANDU Owners Group]] (COG) declared KAPS as the best performing pressurised heavy water reactor.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kurian|first=Vinson|title=Indian N-reactors set new global benchmark|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.in/2003/03/27/stories/2003032702500400.htm|newspaper= [[The Hindu Business Line]]|date=26 March 2003|accessdate=16 February 2017}}</ref>
The construction costs originally were estimated to be ₹ 382.52&nbsp;crore, the plant was finally finished at a price of ₹ 1,335&nbsp;crore. Construction of units 3 & 4 started in November 2010.<ref name="wnn-2211107"/>
== Incidents == * 1998 KAPS-1 was switched off because of a leakage in the cooling loop for 66 days. * 10 March 2004 the (at the time of) supply for the control rods were irreparably damaged during maintenance work. In response, poisons were added to the system and the reactor was shut off. * On 22 August 2006 it was reported by village inhabitants the area around the power station had been penetrated. A search by the police did not result in any findings. * On 11 March 2016, KAPS-1 automatically shut down due to a leak of heavy coolant water, leaving both reactors non-operational.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.aerb.gov.in/AERBPortal/pages/English/prsrel/p11032016.pdf |format= [[PDF]] |website= [[Atomic Energy Regulatory Board|aerb.gov.in]] |title= Shutdown of Unit-1 of KAPS Nuclear Power Plant following an incident leakage from Coolant System |first= S. |last= Harikumar |date= 2016-03-11 |accessdate= 2017-02-16}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.rediff.com/news/report/more-than-100-hours-later-kakrapar-nuclear-leak-not-fixed/20160316.htm|title=More than 100 hours later, Kakrapar nuclear leak not fixed|last=|first=|date=16 March 2016|work=|access-date=18 April 2016|via=Rediff.com}}</ref> The leak was plugged ten days later. {{Asof|March 2017}} both reactors are still shut down and expected to remain so for at least another year.<ref name=timesofindia>{{cite news|url= https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/ahmedabad-no-power-from-kakrapar-plant-for-at-least-a-year/articleshow/57585243.cms |title= Ahmedabad: No power from Kakrapar plant for at least a year |website= [[The Times of India|timesofindia.indiatimes.com]] |date= 2017-03-11 |accessdate= 2017-11-02}}</ref>
